Video Title: Boodle Fight: The Filipino Feast Feeding Hundreds
Video Description:
What‚Äôs a chef to do when hundreds of armed soldiers show up hungry and ready to feast? Well, they boodle, of course! In the Philippines, friends and family gather for a boodle fight, a fabulous feast served atop banana leaves and eaten with bare hands. Traditionally created as a way to feed large numbers of military cadets, people stand shoulder-to-shoulder around a massive table, ready to dive into piles of mouthwatering Filipino delicacies, like grilled pork, adobo and crispy pata. Just be sure to leave your forks and knives at home.

Video Title: FRESHEST SEAFOOD FEAST! INSANE Seafood Meal at Dampa Market Manila Philippines
Video Description:
When I was in Manila Philippines I was told that I HAD to get some FRESH seafood at a local seafood market called Dampa. At this market, you shop for seafood items like fresh fish, crabs, clams, mussels, lobsters and then take the seafood to a number of local restaurants located nearby so they can prepare it for you in a variety of ways.

We also happened to run into a few very friendly friends from Saudia Arabia and went with them to their hotel for a Salmon and Rice feast. After which we returned to the seafood market, selected some fish, crab, clams, and prawns. We then headed for a restaurant called Hong Kong Master Cook and begin one of the most delicious seafood feasts I've ever had!

The seafood was prepared in many different ways and my favorite was the fish cooked in spicy chili broth. Also, the crab was some of the most tender onesI've ever had. I would highly recommend this seafood market if ever in Manila Philipines. 

Dampa Seafood Market:

Video Title: NIGHT MARKET FOOD in Manila Philippines: BBQ & BLOOD STEW
Video Description:
My last night in Manila Philippines and I really wanted to try out one of the local popular night market for some night time eats. One of my local friends suggested Central Mercado a wonderfully vibrant night market in the heart of Manila.

The night market first of all, smelled incredible. From the roasted meat skewers to the refreshing local drinks, there was something for everyone at this night market.

Having filled up on great eats at this night market, I proceeded to a local restaurant that many locals recommended for a taste of Dinuguan which is essentially pork blood stew with organ meat inside.

Video Title: UNSEEN HANGING COFFINS (First YouTube Footage) üíÄSagada, Philippines
Video Description:
The final chapter in my Philippines travel vlog series of exploring the mountain province in Cordillera, Northern Luzon. You're going love love what we found.

We're on the search for hanging coffins in Sagada. As a foreigner in the Philippines, I was told I should go to echo valley to see the famous hanging coffins of the Igorot people. This area gets hundreds of Filipino tourists from Manila, Baguio City, and across the country every day. On Fearless & Far, we're always on the search for the next level. The deeper experience. The adventure that challenges us.
I met up with my guide Chris and Angdung and we grabbed our machetes and hiking boots, and dove into the jungle. Looking for other sites that others have not visited in a long long time. We found exactly that.

The unique death rituals of the mountain people of Cordillera are not for the squeamish.In all my philippines travel vlog experiences, this was perhaps the most shocking and interesting topic I have come across.  

While there are hanging coffins in China, and also similar practices in Indonesia, there's nothing quite like what happens here in Sagada, Mountain Province.

Video Title: Letting NYC Strangers Try Filipino Halo-Halo, THIS was their reaction
Video Description:
We gave random strangers in NYC the amazing Filipino dessert halo-halo to try! They had never had it before and they really loved it! Super cool to see Americans trying halo-halo for the first time, and to spread a bit of Pinoy culture in NYC!

We got it from a small Filipino cafe in NYC called Kabisera that makes the dessert from scratch, including by using their own Filipino ice cream, so it was super authentic and delicious. Made with red bean, jackfruit, ube, Filipino ice cream, shaved ice, condensed milk, coconut, and leche flan. They did not sponsor this video, but they are super nice, and if you want can check them out at: https://www.yelp.com/biz/kabisera-new-york-2

Video Title: Filipino Style BBQ for $1 in the Heart of LA | Street Food Icons
Video Description:
Dollar Hits is a Filipino street food staple in Los Angeles, specializing in meat skewers that cost $1. Customers can cook pork barbecue and chicken barbecue, along with pork ears, chicken feet, and more on charcoal grills outside the restaurant, located in a nondescript mini-mall in downtown LA's Historic Filipinotown. The three sisters who run Dollar Hits immigrated from Pampanga in the Philippines and have since become local street food legends. Other offerings at Dollar Hits include chicken liver, heart, and intestines, fish and lobster balls, and balut, a fertilized duck egg.

Video Title: FILIPINO Family Trying Dutch Food In The Philippines!
Video Description:
In today's latest vlog my (Filipino) family in the Philippines will try Dutch food for the first time...this is a dish called stamppot and is made with a few simple ingredients...I am really curious to see if they will like it or not and so I will do my best to make it very tasty!! No adobo for them this time hehehe

I bought the ingredients here in the Philippines in a grocery store at the shopping mall:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WRHwXkLghAQ&list=PLLihyfqrQKhrrfAnG-BfKg6bzUT5pWxMC&index=2

@TheHungrySyrianWanderer 
Hope you can give it a try and let your family try it ;)

Ingredients:
Dutch MEATBALLS
Ground pork / Ground beef, White or black pepper, Cayenne pepper, Garlic Powder, Soy sauce, Tomato ketchup, Fresh garlic, Egg, Corn starch, Bread crumbs

Dutch STAMPPOT
Potatoes, Carrots, Onions, Salt, Butter

Process:
Mix all the ingredients for the meat balls as shown in the video and shape larger size balls and fry them in butter till done (check inside to see if fully cooked). Peel and cook the potatoes in water and salt (magic sarap can be added if you prefer). Add sliced carrots and onions when potatoes are half cooked, then cook all till done and drain most of the water. Mash everything and add some butter to taste. Serve on a plate with meatballs and gravy...

Video Title: Foreigner Attempts To Cook Filipino Food ‚ÄúDaing Na Bangus‚Äù
Video Description:
In this video you will see Joey a foreigner trying to cook ''Daing na bangus'' a Filipino food.



Daing na bangus is a simple marinated milk fish using just fresh garlic, white vinegar, salt and black pepper and leave it overnight for full flavour. Bangus is very popular all over the Philippines but perhaps most popular in Dagupan City, Pangasinan where they even hold a bangus festival regularly.



In this recipe I will also include a simple sawsawan also known as dipping sauce and it is made from some spicy labuyo peppers, white vinegar, black pepper and chopped onions.


This food is best eaten in Kamayan style which is by using your hands!

Ingredients to make my pancit!
cooking oil
salt
pepper
pancit bihon noodles dry
water
cabbage
carrots
onions
garlic
lemon juice
fatty pork meat
selery or any other fresh herb
chicken stock cubes
soy sauce

Cooking process
Add hot water to the dry noodles and set aside...slice pork in tiny pieces and fry till crispy golden brown, add onions, garlic, pepper and salt and stir well, add carrots and cook till softened a little bit. Afterwards add cabbage and lemon juice and finally the pancit noodles but check that they are soft and completely absorbed the water. you can optionally add the chicken stock cubes which make the dish really delicious so I recommend it as well and finish with some Korean or Japanese soy sauce. Off course you may use a Filipino soy sauce as well!

Video Title: Dutch Family Tries Lechon Belly Filipino Style!!!!
Video Description:
Today I will be giving a ''CRUNCHY'' Filipino food to my Dutch family. The parent tries a Lechon Belly which is a crispy Filipino style dinner! 
 
#pinoyplanet
@featrmedia  what do you think of my lechon belly recipe? :)

You will see my parents Filipino food reaction on this lechon baboy cooked in the oven.
Lechon belly is a special treat for Filipino get togethers.

Sawsawan (dipping sauce):
Soy sauce
White vinegar
White onions
Garlic
Labuyo (spicy Pinoy chili peppers)

Baboy (pork belly):
---Stuffing---
Black pepper
Sea salt
Tanglat (lemon grass)
Spring onions
Sibuyas (White onions)
Bawang (garlic)

---Process---
1. Roll the pork belly and bind
2. Steam in oven at 180C for 2hrs (using tin foil as cover and add water below the pork)
3. Remove foil and add soy sauce on the skin (tip from PINOY PLANET subscribers)
4. Bake crispy in oven at 250C for 1,5hrs

VERY IMPORTANT!! SERVE WITH WARM RICE ;)

Video Title: Filipino Food Pancit Bihon With Dutch Frikandel!!!
Video Description:
In this quick video I will share my super easy and delicious fusion dish which combines Pinoy pancit bihon and Dutch frikandel, PLEASE TRY IT!!

#pinoyplanet
#fusiondish
#frikandel

¬†@Simpol¬† Hope you like this easy recipe!! :)

INGREDIENTS
- Cooking oil
- Pork meat
- Water
- Chicken stock
- Filipino pancit noodles
- Dutch frikandel
- Lemon
- Soy sauce
- Chili pepper
- Chinese cabbage (spitskool works best)
- Carrots
- Onions - Garlic

Pre-heat oven to 220C and add Dutch frikandel (check package for exact directions), Cut pork meat and add to boiling water in wok, after getting soft and water has been gone please add some cooking oil to make it extra crispy. Add onions, garlic, carrots, chicken stock cube and mix well. Add cabbage, chili peppers, pancit bihon noodles and lemon juice as well as the soy sauce.

Finish by adding the frikadel (cut in tiny pieces) and use toppings such as fresh parsley and spring onions.

Please enjoy!!

Video Title: This Gyoza Dumpling Contains Filipino Food........
Video Description:

#pinoyplanet

SISIG RECIPE:
deepfry pork meat till crispy, let cool off and then chop in tiny pieces. Refry in some butter or margarine and add about one onion (also finely chopped), add garlic powder, black pepper and a little bit of soy sauce as well as mayonaise then add chili peppers, lime juice and the remaining part of the chopped onions. Turn the heat off and let cool off.

DUMPLINGS:
Fill the gyoza skins and fold them add a little bit of water so that they can stick. fry on low heat till crispy golden brown, then add some water (not too much) and cover till cooked well!

Video Description:
I‚Äôm a Dutch man who tries to cook all kind of delicious Filipino food and today I will try to make the lechon belly more tasty than before!

In this new playlist I will make more tasty food and will try to make it even more tasty than before (ASMR)! First the lechon belly! At Pinoy Planet I like to cook Filipino food in all kind of varieties so please enjoy this new series in 2022!

FULL RECIPE:
Take the lechon belly out of the freezer and let it defrost in the fridge overnight, take a paper towel and remove excess moist, add black pepper, salt, chili flakes and garlic powder inside as well as chives and crushed lemon grass. Roll the lechon belly and tie up with kitchen twine. Steam in steamer for about 30 min, then let cool off, wrap in plastic and put in the freezer for 2hrs.

Afterwards pre-heat the oven at 250C and rub the pork belly with salt, bake for 1,5hr then let cool off for 15-30 min and finally about 15min under the grill, watch continously since some pieces could burn quickly. Very crackling and crunchy for sure and a must try!!

Video Title: My Dutch Nephew And His Girlfriend Try Bicol Express!
Video Description:
Today I will bring a ''VERY TASTY'' Filipino food to my Dutch nephew and his girlfriend. They will try bicol express for the first time and enjoy this Filipino dish in combination with some crackling chicharon! 

#pinoyplanet
@ToniGonzagaStudio Hope you like my Pinoy dish:)

This time you will see my nephew's Filipino food reaction on this spicy food from Bicol, Philippines. Bicol express is such a Pinoy treat!

BICOL EXPRESS WITH A STORY: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BZA1TUcHa4k&list=PLLihyfqrQKhol7mfMkr3QwnWJ8I8vj70H
LECHON BELLY FOR MY PARENTS: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vrwkd3W1lD0&list=PLLihyfqrQKhoSVv76Y-El1Z2EubTBkHTj
LECHON BELLY FOR MY UNCLES AND AUNTIES: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Er-rt3DAw_I&list=PLLihyfqrQKhoSVv76Y-El1Z2EubTBkHTj&index=4

Ingredients:
2,5KG baboy
black pepper
1L of coconutmilk
1 super spicy red chili pepper
5 or 6 green chili peppers 
Bagoong alamang
Little extra salt
Garlic
Onions
A little bit of sugar

PROCESS
1. Add baboy to hot pan without oil
2. Add some black pepper
3. Add Bagoong shrimp paste after pork meat gets crispy
4. Add coconutmilk, then red chili, green chili and sugar and mix well
5. Let the coconutmilk get thicker till the pork fat comes out!

Serve on warm rice together with some delicious chicharon baboy!

Video Title: Dutch Parents Try Classic Filipino Food Ginisang Monggo!
Video Description:
I am back in the Netherlands so today it is very exciting that my parents will try again Filipino food and this time a classic ginisang monggo!! 

#filipinofood 

--Ingredients--
rice, monggo beans, spinach, pork meat, pepper, salt, patis (fish sauce), chicken stock, onions, garlic, ginger

--Process--
I leave the munggo beans in water for several hours before boiling, then I boil the beans gently and in a separate sauce pan I fry the pork meat in a little bit of oil with black pepper and salt. After that I fry onions, garlic and ginger and add both the pork and the onion mix to the beans and water with a cube of chicken stock. Then I simmer it and once the beans are cooked I will add the fish sauce and spinach and serve on top of the rice!

VERY IMPORTANT!! SERVE WITH WARM RICE ;)

Video Title: Dutch Parents Try Classic Filipino Food Pork ADOBONG PUTI!
Video Description:
Your recipe will be cooked today :) Please send me more so that my parents can try more Filipino food! Today it will be pork adobo or adobong puti a special family recipe sent from the Philippines by Ms. Kriss Tina, I am so happy to cook it here in the Netherlands and bring it to my parents!

Watch More From This Classic Filipino Food Series On Pinoy Planet:
GINISANG MONGGO: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N30eSJCl5Cs&list=PLLihyfqrQKhotAfCUbAZqGC1Pexu_JvoW&index=1
PANCIT CANTON: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mRGsu99YAPQ&list=PLLihyfqrQKhotAfCUbAZqGC1Pexu_JvoW&index=2

#filipinofood 

--Ingredients--
fatty pork cubes (belly), black pepper, cooking oil, garlic, bay leaves, Thai red chili, coconut vinegar, boiling water, Sprite (or something  similar), salt, rice and broccoli

--Process--
I cut the baboy into big chunks, fry them in oil to get them super crispy, add bawang, put coconut vinegar and cover without stirring, add water and cover again waiting till the meat gets tender, add Sprite or similar lemonade, add salt, black pepper, bay leaves, Thai chili and keep lid off now till sauce thickens, I kept it a little saucy this time but a drier version is also nice if you have the time, maraming salamat po!!

VERY IMPORTANT!! SERVE WITH WARM RICE ;)

Video Title: Trying To Make Filipino Chicken Adobo More Tasty Than Before!!
Video Description:
I‚Äôm a foreigner (Dutch) who loves to cook Filipino food and today I try to make chicken Adobo more tasty than before!
In this new playlist I will make more tasty food and will try to make it even more tasty than before (ASMR)! In this second episode chicken adobo! At Pinoy Planet I like to cook Filipino food in all kind of varieties so please enjoy this new series in 2022!

#filipinofood
#foreignoy
#pinoyplanet

PART 1 (LECHON BELLY):

FULL RECIPE:
Add some cooking oil to a pan and briefly fry the chicken drum sticks on medium to high heat golden brown on both sides and set aside. Then Add chopped garlic and onions and fry a bit. Afterwards add the chicken back and and cane vinegar from the Philippines + authentic soy sauce! Then add black pepper, salt, bay leaves and one finely chopped chili. Cover and gently boil for about 20 min, then flip over and repeat for another 20 minutes. Serve with warm rice!! Tastes even better the next day! Filipino style!!

Video Description:

Recipes I followed:
Indonesian Internet: http://www.kimchiandbeans.com/2020/05/how-to-make-indonesian-internet.html (¬†@Maria and Nabol - Kimchi & Beans¬† )

USA Fritters: 
Boil  diced potato and keep some water when they are done. In a frying pan. with some butter add 2 chopped green onions, chopped garlic and diced corned beef. Cook until crispy.
Add the potato and stir. Add a bit of the reserved liquid. 
Prepare pancake batter per package instructions. Add the corned beef hash and put in the fridge for at least 1/2 hour (can do overnight!).
Fry pancakes with a bit of oil until golden brown. Serve with ketchup or yogurt, OR yogurt mixed with horseradish!  
 
Bahamian Fire Engine: http://thebitchinkitchin.blogspot.com/2014/03/bahamian-fire-engine.html
Australia Baked Macaroni: 
Nanna Barbara‚Äôs Baked Macaroni
Ingredients
1 x 500g/1lbs bag of tube pasta (nan likes penne, I like rigatoni, so choose your favourite but it must be a tube style)
1 x medium sized brown onion
1 x tin of corned beef
1 x cup of water
1 x 500g jar of tomato paste (use less if you prefer)
1 x desert spoon (or to taste) of mild curry powder*
4 x eggs
100g grated parmesan cheese**
salt to taste
Cooking Instructions
1. Bring a large pot of salted water to boil to cook pasta
2. Pre-heat fan forced oven to 180C/350F 
3. While the pasta is cooking, dice the onion and saut√© until soft
4. Chop corned beef into small blocks and add to the onion, then add water and break up the blocks to soften
5. Add tomato paste, curry powder and salt to the corned beef mixture and stir to combine
6. When the pasta is done cooking, drain and transfer to a large baking dish
7. Pour over the corned beef sauce and mix to coat all the pasta
8. In a small bowl whisk the eggs with half the parmesan cheese, then pour over the pasta and mix to combine
9. Sprinkle the rest of the cheese over the top of the pasta and bake until brown and crispy
10. Enjoy!

Video Title: Mobile Stores & Pop-Up Shops with Cebu Philippines Classic Riders | John Smulo
Video Description:
Last week, we interviewed Paul about The Coffee Mobile and how their mobile store started the street coffee culture in the Philippines.

üì£ If you want to support me and my mission, please consider joining our channel membership. You'll get access to perks such as loyalty badges, custom emojis, priority replies, exclusive live videos, and more! Join here: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCKie0svsFyBBsKaQIA4hx-w/join üëà

Today, I'm back to check out some mobile stores and pop up shops here that were started by a group of classic motorcycle riders in Cebu Philippines.

They have various types of food like tacos, sandwiches, braised quail eggs, lumpia, and for vegetarians, fried noodles.

A van also sells handmade accessories, stickers, and sun-dried fish (bulad) from Bantayan Island.

The community is more like a close-knit family with similar interests and, in this case, classic motorcycles and food.

It's a totally unique experience as you see awesome classic motorcycles while your food is being cooked on the motorcycle itself.

If you're ever in Cebu Philippines, make sure to visit these mobile stores and pop up shops and restaurants. You can find their daily location through the links below:

SUBSCRIBE! If you made your own boodle fight/kamayan feast at home, what would YOU put on the menu?! I hope this video helps you prepare your own feast at home.

In this video, I prepare a boodle fight, aka a kamayan feast, aka "pile a bunch of filipino food on top of banana leaves and eat with your hands" feast! Half of the food I prepared from scratch, and the other half I purchased pre-marinated or fully cooked.

Make sure you properly plan out your menu and your schedule so you don't get overwhelmed. With only one person cooking and a few hours to do it, I had to make sure I was organized.

We had 10 people total (7 adults, 3 children), and had plenty of leftovers afterwards!

Video Title: Eating STREET FOOD in WORLDS OLDEST CHINATOWN üáµüá≠  Binondo Manila Philippines
Video Description:
What an awesome day in Manila! We spent the day in the worlds OLDEST chinatown! Dating back to 1594! Even though you may think its old, the food, flavour and culture is still very much ALIVE here in the Philippines, and it certainly did not disappoint! 

In this video we venture around Chinatown also known as Binondo and get totally stuck into a wide variety of food and flavour! Our very first street food tour in the Philippines!

First up is Dong Bei Dumplings - excellent pork and chive dumplings 200 Pesos for 14! What a deal!
Next up we try Calamansi juice for the first time! 80 Pesos 
Lumpia (Giant vegetable burrito/spring roll - very delicious - 95 Pesos 
Shanghai Fried Siopao - this was the HIGHLIGHT of the food journey we had today! The most delicious steamed bun for only 30 Pesos, we can see why this was so popular!

Video Title: THE BEST CHICKEN INASAL IN THE PHILIPPINES? üáµüá≠ BACOLOD CITY FOOD TOUR PLUS CANSI
Video Description:
There was no way we were going to come all the way to Bacolod City and not try the foods üòç. We've heard from so many of you that the food here is a must try and honestly you guys...you were NOT LYING üò±

The most famous of them all is probably the chicken inasal.  For those of you not familiar with chicken inasal, chicekn inasal is a variant of Filipino chicken dish called lechon manok.  It's marinated in a mixture of ingredients including calamansi, coconut vinegar, annatto, and more and then grilled over hot coals while based in the marinate. It's a barbeque style that honestly you guys, you MUST TRY if you haven't already.

In this vlog we take you to one of the most well known places for chicken inasal: Neena Beths, but we've also visited Chicken House and Coyoca here in Bacolod (not in the video) and we must confess they just as incredible!  And don't worry we made our way to Sharyn's too also try cansi, a special semi-sour beef soup which originated in Bacolod ‚ù§Ô∏è

We suggest anyone and everyone that makes their way to Bacolod City to try all the foods üòç. They clearly have their own signature styles and rank most certainly in the top 2 of the best we've yet to have in the 7 months of our time in the Philippines üò±

Video Title: EUROPEANS FIRST TIME EAT JOLLIBEE PHILIPPINES üáµüá≠
Video Description:

Is Philippines good for expats? 
The Philippines is a top-rated destination for expatriates. The country has a warm climate, friendly people, welcoming culture, and low living costs make the country an ideal destination for expats. 

Where do most expats live in Philippines? 
Most expats in the Philippines live in the Metro Manila area, particularly in Makati City ‚Äì home to many international corporations and the heart of the country's diplomatic community. 

Can a US citizen live permanently in the Philippines? 
Yes, under the Philippine Immigration Act of 1940, Section 13 (a) you are eligible for permanent residency in the Philippines. Is retiring in the Philippines a good idea? Retiring in the Philippines can be a great escape when done right. Overall, you're going to notice goods and services are cheaper than they are in the U.S. You can also find affordable healthcare as long as you retire in a location close to hospitals. However, certain parts lack infrastructure and investment.

Philippines Tourism Tourism is an important sector for Philippine economy. 

In 2019, the travel and tourism industry contributed 12.7% to the country's GDP.[1] Philippines is an archipelagic country composed of 7,641 islands with 81 provinces divided in 17 regions. The country is known for having its rich biodiversity as its main tourist attraction. Its beaches, heritage towns and monuments, mountains, rainforests, islands and diving spots are among the country's most popular tourist destinations. 

The country's rich historical and cultural heritage, including its festivals and indigenous traditions, are also one of the attractions of Philippines. Popular destinations among tourists are Cebu, Boracay, Palawan, Siargao, and many more.

Video Title: My Favourite Chicken in the Philippines - Amazing $3 Filipino Chicken. The Best Fast Food Chain
Video Description:
Kumusta my friends, 

Back to another episode here in the Philippines, we are trying another popular fast food chain called Mang Inasal, which is well known for their grilled chicken. Going into the restaurant we had no expectations, but our minds were blown as soon as we went in. Firstly, the staff at the restaurant greeted us with enthusiasm. Secondly, we walked in and immediately saw chefs preparing the mouth watering chicken behind the glass window. We ordered the Pecho Chicken Set which comes with a big chicken, rice, soft drinks and we also ordered the empanada. It costed 252 pesos in total which is 6.6AUD/ 4.4USD. 

The chicken came faster than expected and the smell was on the next level. As soon as I took my first bite, all the memories from childhood came back from 10 years ago when I first visited Cebu and had roast chicken on the streets. It had the exact same taste. I rated this fast food chain the best in the Philippines as it is definitely my personal favourite.

Title: Hong Kong Russian Couple Trying Chinese Filipino Fast Food - Chowking

If you are wondering what is the best things to do in the Philippines 2022, you have come to the right channel. Coming to the Philippines, we had two goals. One is to understand and learn about the culture of the Philippines. Second, is to try the all the filipino food.

Video Title: Foreigner reacts to KARINDERYA Philippines  üáµüá≠ Eating like a FILIPINO LOCAL
Video Description:
Kumusta YouTube fam, 

As many of our subscribers might know, Alina and I are huge foodies and are always open to trying new food. 4 months into living in the Philippines we have made numerous Filipino food reaction videos from the best soup in the world - Filipino Sinigang to the unique peanut dish Kare Kare to some of our favourite Filipino Inasals at fast food or roadside vendors, but one particular Filipino style restaurant we haven't tried was the famous budget canteens carinderias, where home-style Filipino cooking are displayed in trays and the locals can point and choose what they want.

In this episode, I met up with one of my subscribers Gelo and went on a food adventure to a local carinderia called Aling Sosing situated in Makakati where I gave my first impression of carinderia in the Philippines. Growing up in Hong Kong and Australia, my family is not very used to tasting the internal organs of animals, such as chicken hearts, pork liver and intestines etc so I was very sceptical about trying them when we first arrived. However part of the reason why I decided to travel full-time is that I want to embrace different cultural experiences. We tried a variety of dishes and overall had a great experience eating on the roadside.

Video Title: Foreigners Learn How to Cook PHILIPPINES SINIGANG üáµüá≠ The Best Soup in the World
Video Description:
Kumusta YouTube fam, 

Welcome to a new episode here in the beautiful city of Manila the Philippines. Throwback to 4 months ago when we first came to the Philippines, the first Filipino dish that we were introduced to is the "best soup in the world", sour soup Sinigang. Sinigang is a Filipino soup or stew characterized by its sour and savoury taste. It is most often associated with tamarind, although it can use other sour fruits and leaves as the souring agent. It is one of the more popular dishes in Filipino cuisine. The soup is usually accompanied by rice. After settling into our apartment, we finally are ready to take on a Sinigang cooking challenge. 

We invited our friend Joy who can also speak fluent Russian, she is able to communicate fluently in Russian with Alina which is a bonus, to teach us how to cook traditional Filipino Sinigang. We first met up at BGC Landmark to grab all the ingredients necessary for making the soup then we started cooking Sinigang for 1.5 hours.

Join us as we teach you how to make Sinigang!

Video Title: Jollibee OMG! Hong Kong Russian Couple Trying Jollibee for the First Time. The Best Fast Food Chain
Video Description:
Title: Jollibee OMG! Hong Kong Russian Couple Trying Jollibee for the First Time. The Best Fast Food Chain

If you are wondering what is the best things to do in the Philippines 2022, you have come to the right channel. Coming to the Philippines, we had two goals. One is to understand and learn about the culture of the Philippines. Second, is to try the most popular filipino fast food chain - Jollibee. Just kidding, but trying Jollibee is definitely high up on our bucket list. 

Finally today is the day. We arrived in the hustling and bustling district of Divisoria and tried Jollibee. Upon arrival, my first impression was that Jollibee felt a bit like KFC with all the fried chicken options. However as I looked at the menu closely, Jollibee offers a wider variety of options such as spaghetti, mushroom sauce on meat patty with rice and even special pies. 

Alina and I ordered the set which comes with the signature Jollibee spaghetti, meat patty with mushroom sauce, fried chicken and we also ordered 2 ice cream, cheesy hot dog and mango pie on top of that. Everything was amazing and as I mentioned in the video it was one of my favourite fast food experience. No wonder so many Filipinos highly recommend Jollibee.

Video Title: how to make SISIG and PALABOK | Filipino Cooking
Video Description:
This is an authentic sisig recipe and palabok recipe. We are in the Philippines to see my parents.  We asked Janet and her sisters to teach us how to make our favorite filipino food in a very filipino way! If you ever wondered how to cook Sisig or how to cook Palabok, this could possibly be the video for you.  Enjoy our truly Filipino Food home cooking video. 

//Timeline//

1:04 Sisig Ingredients
-pig ear
-pig belly
-green chilis
-red chilis
-garlic
-calamansi
-liquid seasoning


1:23 Steps - Sisig
-Boil the rinsed pig ears and belly till it's tender
-Chop up vetetables
-Take the meat out of the pot and chop it up
-Fry the chopped meat in the oiled pan
-Close the lid and put it on low heat
-Add liquid seasoning
-Add all of the vegetables in to the pan
-Add calamansi juice
-Spread butter on heated sizzling plate

3:00 Palabok Ingredients
-smoke fish
-ground pork
-shrimp
-garlic
-green onion
-eggs
-pancit noodles
-calamansi
-pork rinds (chicharon)

3:13 Steps - Palabok
-Cook both side of the smoke fish
-Strip out the meat and mince it up
-Boil washed shrimp in the salted water
-Cook the pork after wash it
-Add alt and soy sauce
-Make the gravy sauce
-Cook the rice noodles
-Crumble the pork rinds
-Put everything in layers in a party plate

Video Title: Little Manila - New York City Asian Food Gem üá∫üá∏üáµüá≠
Video Description:
One of the best way to explore filipino culture is to taste their filipino cuisine. Here in Little Manila,  located in Woodside, Queens - This is the best place in New York City to explore variety of filipino restaurants which the one we visited and show you in this video literally gave the exact authentic taste just like the cuisine we tried in the philippines.

We went to Kabayan in little Manila and we are not disappointed by the taste. The food we ordered are Bulalo, which is the restaurant's specialty. We also tried sisig, which jimmy said the taste is exactly like the one he tried in the Philippines. Filipino BBQ chicken is also superb - the marinated sauce totally make it amazing.

About Divertliving

American and Thai travel couple left the career in military and finance to become travel story teller. We met in 2015 in South Korea when Jimmy was in U.S. army and Tah studied for bachelor degree. In 2017, September, we both started traveling and created ' divertliving ' to share with world that we are not rich, but we can still travel well and enjoy our life. The content is uploaded almost everyday, providing real travel experience, traveling tips, struggle we have been through while traveling. You will see how it is like traveling as a mixed couple, it is greatly challenging in terms of cultural difference ( and so many more differences )

Video Title: NYC Things To Do - Best Experience with local New Yorker üá∫üá∏
Video Description:
Full day trip experiencing NYC with our local New Yorker Friends. Stating off in Manhattan which we visit plenty of both famous and hidden place all around like the whispering wall at Grand Central Station in NYC which is the location filmed in a couple of movies as well. 

We also got a chance to have a short walk sight seeing New York Public Library ( NYPL) We never planned to visit the public library while in New York City but we were walking right by on the fifth avenue so we went in and found out that This is not just the library It's like a museum !  Wandering around inside, we found out that it is actually the scene we saw in movie Day after Tomorrow and we were amazed by architecture, massive art work, and special exhibits., It is a place of refuge from the madness of¬† New York city.

We also visited the first major landscaped public park in the US. Get a thorough look into the heart of New York City, the Central Park in Manhattan.
____

Video Title: 3 Best Las Vegas Filipino Restaurants! DELISH Filipino Food!
Video Description:
Looking for where to eat the best Filipino food in Las Vegas? Travelling Foodie Raymond Cua takes you on a food tour of 3 of the best Filipino restaurants in Las Vegas.

‚û£ Las Vegas Playlist: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QJjaOz9-3Wg&list=PL-wQeGXw6xB5CbRdXuxib0CgyIDLAy01j

This Las Vegas food vlog features the following Filipino restaurants, all of which are off-the-strip:

1) Tina's Filipino Cuisine - 7720 S Jones Blvd, Unit 105, Las Vegas, NV 89139, United States - Amazing lechon kawali! Crispy Pata is delish too though I still prefer D'Pinoy Joint for it. The lunch special is a great deal at Tina's Filipino Cuisine. I love that it doubles as a sari-sari store for Filipino goodies too.

2) Mang Felix Kitchen - 7080 S Rainbow Blvd, Las Vegas, NV 89118, United States - I love that this Mang Felix Kitchen does both Filipino and Vietnamese food and not as a fusion! The Oxtail Pho is delicious with comforting broth and big pieces of oxtail. The Sizzling Pares is a must-try! Never saw Filipino beef pares made like this before. And the beef tapa is nice and flavourful (and not dry unlike most)!

3) D‚ÄôPinoy Joint - 7680 S Las Vegas Blvd, Las Vegas, NV 89123, United States - D'Pinoy Joint is one of the best restaurants in Las Vegas for traditional Filipino food and has the most extensive menu of Filipino dishes for you to try! Their Bicol Express is one of the best I've had and the Crispy Pata is the best I've had in Las Vegas.

Video Title: Eating LECHON for the first time CEBU CITY, PHILIPPINES (Sugbo Mercado)
Video Description:
#filipinofood #lechon

#SugboMercado, a night market located in I.T park Cebu City,
When we first saw "night market" on the map, we instantly thought of the night markets in Taipei we had visited a few weeks back, 
https://youtu.be/W6E1m6wV3UM

but we were surprised to find that it was m ore akin to the smorgasborg in new york city.
https://youtu.be/8K2gp6ZzN9A

It was certainly a pleasant surprise, filled with delicious food and very enthusiastic food vendors that are happy to talk to you about their culinary creations.

We found a variety and mix of food, from pasta to takoyaki, teobokki, noodles, pad Thai and lots and lots of barbecue, which is evident in the smokey and delicious air.

but we were determined to find some local food, so we each take 500 Piso, which we come to find out was way way too much, and we go out on a hunt for some local food.

sorry, no balut! (Daniel is happy about this)

We also opted to walk everywhere, which we found to be a lot more interesting, interacting with the local people.. no tourists! we loved it!

We are back to our daily lives of working and exploring the fabulous city we live in NYC, but we will be uploading three times a week, with travel vlogs on tuesdays and thursdays, and NYC vlogs on Sundays.

Video Title: Street Food Philippines 2022! BEST LUGAW IN MALOLOS BULACAN? CHEAP Filipino Street Food - Lugaw Goto
Video Description:
Lugaw or Porridge in general is traditionally thought of as food for the sick people due to the fact that it's bland, easy to eat, and fulfilling. It's also eaten for breakfast to start the day with a hearty warm bowl. Today, since I'm a little bit under the weather, we're going to start our Malolos Bulacan Food trip at Lugaw ni Abel! We had the following:

* Lugaw
* Laman
* Dila
* Tuwalya

Video Title: Filipino Restaurant Challenge w/ Lumpia, Pancit, and Chicken Adobo!!
Video Description:
A&Z #1033 - professional eater Randy Santel versus the giant "Sari Not Sorry" Filipino Food Restaurant Challenge w/ Lumpia, Pancit, and Chicken Adobo hosted by A Taste of Manila in Wausau, Wisconsin!! A Taste of Manila is owned by Ed and Marjorie Giallombardo, and they host "ghost kitchens" and pop-up restaurants at bars, distilleries, and vendors around the Wausau, Wisconsin area. They thankfully invited @KatinaEatsKilos and I up to help kick off their new restaurant challenge as part of an event held at Timekeeper Distillery owned by their friends Dan and Kim. For this "Sari Not Sorry" Filipino Restaurant Eating Challenge, I had 45 minutes to feast on 8 giant pork lumpia, 2 softball-sized mounds of garlic fried rice, a giant portion of Filipino pancit with rice noodles and healthy vegetables, and 3 pieces of Filipino chicken adobo served with enough potatoes to fill up the plate. I enjoyed some optional dipping sauces plus 2 of their Westside Tasty Treat ice cream options - Mango Float and Berry Float. Both were yummy!! Courtesy of Timekeeper Distillery, I enjoyed a canned coattail with gin plus an old-fashioned made with bourbon. I was trying to become the 2nd person to win my $45 Filipino meal free plus a spot on the Wall of Fame!! Thanks to Ed & Marjorie with A Taste of Manila, Dan & Kim with Timekeeper Distillery, and everyone involved with the event for the delicious food, drinks, ice cream desserts, and hospitality!! Special thanks to everyone from around the Wausau area who came up to watch and meet us that January evening. We appreciate everyone in Wausau, WI and around Wisconsin who watches and supports our hard efforts!!

Can Randy conquer this Filipino Restaurant Challenge w/ Lumpia, Pancit, and Chicken Adobo??

A Taste of Manila's "Sari Not Sorry" Filipino Restaurant Challenge in Wausau, Wisconsin ($45):

- A Taste of Manila first operated at Westside Tasty Treat located in Wausau, Wisconsin. 
- Now they mainly do pop-up kitchens at bars, distilleries, and vendors around the area.
- This event was hosted at Timekeeper Distillery, very well known around the Wausau area. 
- "Sari" is a Filipino word meaning "variety" and there was a lot of variety with this challenge. 
- For this restaurant challenge, there is a 45 minute time limit to finish lots of tasty Filipino dishes. 
- There are 8 giant pork lumpia and 3 pieces of chicken adobo with potatoes that fill up the plate. 
- There are 2 softball-sized scoops of garlic fried rice plus a huge portion of tasty Filipino Pancit.
- I added on to my challenge, 2 of their Westside Tasty Treat ice creams with Mango and Berries.
- From Timekeeper Distillery, I enjoyed 1 of their canned gin drinks plus a bourbon Old-Fashioned. 
- Restaurant challenge winners earn the $45 Filipino meal free plus a spot on their Wall of Fame!!

Video Title: Lola's Lumpia $100 Filipino Food Truck Challenge!!
Video Description:
A&Z #881 - Randy Santel "Atlas" vs Lola's Lumpia $100 Filipino Food Truck Challenge hosted by Lola's Lumpia Food Truck outside Oak Road Brewery in Summerville, South Carolina!! After finishing up my food challenges in North Carolina, I traveled down to South Carolina where I attempted lots of delicious food challenges as part of my 2020 Southeast USA Tour. For event #3, I traveled down to Summerville, South Carolina which is just outside Charleston, SC. I was the first person to attempt and I helped kick off the Lola's Lumpia $100 Food Truck Challenge hosted by Lola's Lumpia Food Truck outside Oak Road Brewery. I had 45 minutes to finish lots of traditional Filipino foods which were so delicious!! There were 48 lumpia total which the food truck is known for, with 16 / Each of 3 different meats - chicken, pork, and beef. I also got to enjoy an adobo pulled pork sandwich, 1/2lb of Filipino pancit, 2 Siopao, a big handful of shrimp chips, and I tried drinking 3 delicious beers produced by Oak Road Brewery. I was trying to win my $100 Filipino food truck dinner free, a sweet t-shirt, and the first spot on Lola's Wall of Fame. Thank you to Mark and his wife (Lola's owners) and their team for the wonderful food and hospitality, and thanks also to Ben (owner of Oak Road Brewery) and his team for the delicious beers and drinks!! Thanks also to everyone who came that Sunday to watch and meet me!! I appreciate everyone around the Summerville, SC area and throughout the state of South Carolina who supports our efforts!! There are many more videos upcoming!!

Lola's Lumpia $100 Filipino Food Truck Challenge in Summerville, South Carolina ($100):

- Lola's Lumpia Food Truck serves the greater Charleston area, including Summerville, SC.
- Their specialty is serving Filipino lumpia which are 1oz fried Filipino-style spring rolls. 
- For this food truck challenge, you must finish 48 of them (3lbs total) with 3 different meats. 
- There are 16 with chicken, 16 with beef, and 16 with pork, and you get both of their sauces.
- The challenge includes 2 Siopao (pork steamed buns), shrimp chips, and 1/2 lb of pancit.
- There is also a delicious pulled pork adobo sandwich topped with slaw and some sauces. 
- My challenge took place at Oak Road Brewery. The beers I drank were only to promote the brewery and they were not part of the actual food challenge. The base food challenge has no drink requirements. 
- There is a 45 minute time limit. Winners get the $100 Filipino meal free and a sweet Lola's t-shirt.

Video Title: Is This The BEST Filipino Restaurant in Malaysia?! üáµüá≠ (Kuala Lumpur Mukbang üá≤üáæ)
Video Description:
Right before arriving in Kuala Lumpur City, Malaysia, I spent a month traveling in the Philippines. But since I've been constantly moving from country to country, it takes my body a couple of days to adjust to new, local dishes. I was craving Filipino food and luckily, someone I met earlier that week recommend Mabuhay Laguna Restaurant so I could satisfy my cravings!

Mabuhay Laguna Restaurant Location: 3, Jalan Gereja, City Centre, 55000 Kuala Lumpur, Wilayah Persekutuan Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.

Video Title: Look what we found in Bohol, Philippines!
Video Description:
üëâüèºüëâüèº üáµüá≠ Let's help YouTube spread the beauty of the Philippines to as much of the world as possible! Like, comment, and subscribe so that this episode gets maximum reach üëçüèº

We‚Äôre about two-thirds of the way through our 21-day tour of Southeast Asia and so far we‚Äôve experienced the beautiful city of Singapore, the world‚Äôs oldest Chinatown in Manila, the tribal lagoons of Coron, and the resort-heavy island of Boracay. Today, we‚Äôre packing up and heading southeast to experience the natural wonders of Bohol‚Äîand to find out why this destination is one of the most popular in the Philippines. But once again, getting there means first flying back up to Manila and then catching the connecting flight back down.

Unlike the tiny island of Boracay that we just left, Bohol is on the bigger side‚Äîit‚Äôs the 10th largest in the Philippines. It‚Äôs actually one big island and 75 minor surrounding islands. We flew into and staying on one of those minor islands‚ÄîPanglao‚Äîjust off the southwestern tip of the main island. In fact, it‚Äôs so close that you can drive to it using either of two bridges that span the causeway.

The most popular attraction in Bohol is Chocolate Hills: 1,776 limestone hills stretched over 50 square kilometers of the island. They are covered in green grass that turns brown during the dry season, hence the name. Formed by tectonic shifts that pushed them upwards and then smoothed into conical hills by water erosion. These iconic hills are even featured in the 200 Philippine Peso bill.

Video Title: Filipino Street Food Tour - BALUT and KWEK KWEK at Quiapo Market, Manila, Philippines!
Video Description:
Anton and I go on an extreme Filipino street food snack tour of Quiapo Market!
‚ñ∫Check out Anton‚Äôs channel: https://www.youtube.com/user/antondiaz
‚ñ∫Subscribe to my channel for more videos: http://bit.ly/MarkWiensSubscribe

The area around Quiapo Church, is home to a huge market, where you‚Äôll find an abundance of especially clothing and street food - and ranging from fresh ingredients to cooked food ready to eat. If you love to eat, when you‚Äôre in Manila, Quiapo Market is one of the best places to start and get a feel for the city and eat some amazing Filipino street food.

We started right at Quiapo Church and it happened to be a Sunday afternoon - Anton mentioned that it‚Äôs usually the busiest on Sunday afternoon, catering to everyone that attends the hourly church service. We walked down one alley and ate two noodle dishes palabok (20 PHP, $0.40) and sotanghon (30 PHP, $0.60). Both dishes were good, and served fresh. I especially enjoyed the sotanghon, a cellophane noodles dish, that was cooked in flavorful oil and it was a perfect slurping dish.

Right in front of Quiapo Church in Manila, we at first though they were fish balls or squid balls, but they turned out to be chicken balls (2 PHP, $0.04 per ball). In order to eat Filipino chicken balls, you grab a stick, poke some on your stick, and dip in vinegar. They weren‚Äôt the best quality, but they weren‚Äôt expensive either. Next to the chicken balls, I saw the dried squid (10 PHP, $0.20 per stick) and had to try it as well. It was amazing, dried chewy squid, roasted over charcoal and dunked in chili vinegar.

We then walked across the main road at Quiapo and found a Filipino street food stall serving all types of kwek kwek (3 for 12 PHP, $0.24). Kwek kwek is a popular street food of quail eggs, coated in a thick batter and deep fried. We also tried 1 day old fried chickens (10 PHP, $0.20), which is another popular Filipino street food in that area of Manila. As with other Filipino snacks, you garnish with chilies, shallots, and lots of vinegar before eating.

Probably one of the most famous of all Philippines street food is balut (15 PHP, $.030), a duck egg embryo - like a half developed egg. You‚Äôll find balut all over the Philippines and it‚Äôs especially popular to eat in the evening. The first thing you do is crack the top of the egg shell and drink the chicken soup. You then peel the rest of the egg, and eat both chick and the yolk on the inside. I also seasoned with a little salt and chili vinegar. I‚Äôve eaten balut quite a few times during many trips to the Philippines, and I quite enjoy eating balut!

Quiapo Market is a wonderful place in Manila to explore all the street food snacks available, and it‚Äôs just an amazingly vibrant and colorful part of Manila, and it was great to hang out with Anton!

Thank you for watching!

Video Title: Philippines Street Food - AMAZING Filipino Food at Aling Sosing's Carinderia in Manila!
Video Description:
One of the best Filipino food meals you can eat in Manila!
‚ñ∫Subscribe to my channel for more food videos: http://bit.ly/MarkWiensSubscribe

Aling Sosing's is often considered to be one of the best carinderias, or local Filipino food restaurants, in all of Manila. The crowd that shows up to eat lunch here everyday reinforces the fact that they are no doubt one of the spots you want to be in Manila, if you‚Äôre a food lovers. When I was eating in Manila, eating at Aling Sosing's was certainly among the best local Filipino food restaurants that I tried.

Aling Sosing's is a very typical type of local street food restaurant, sitting on the corner of a street, near to Makati. Just like most carinderias, all the food is prepared ahead of time, and sits at the front of the restaurant. When you arrive to order, you just simply pick and choose the different dishes that you want to order, find a table, and they will bring you the dishes to your table. Additionally, some of the famous dishes to eat at Aling Sosing's are off the grill, and you‚Äôll smell the wonderful aroma of the grilling meats the entire time you‚Äôre eating, and it‚Äôs fantastic.

Ying and I arrived about 11 am on a weekday, and luckily we beat the main lunch traffic, but just barely. There were tables available when we arrived, but as soon as we sat down and order it filled up. Sof if you eat at Aling Sosing's Carinderia you might want to arrive before the main lunch rush. Additionally, some of the Filipino food dishes sell out fast, and they don‚Äôt cook them again for the day - once they are sold out, they are done for the day.

Here are the main Filipino dishes I ordered:
Pinakbet - A stew of mixed vegetables, oftentimes flavored with shrimp paste. This was the best versions of pinakbet I‚Äôve ever had.
Inihaw na tilapia - The grilled tilapia is quite well known at this restaurant. It was simple and delicious.
Inihaw na liempo - The grilled pork belly is one of their signature dishes, and it‚Äôs every bit as good and smoky as it looks.
Kaldereta - A Filipino food I love so much is kaldereta, a goat stew, mainly because I love goat so much. It was oily, but really good.
Adobong pusit - I saw the squid the pot and decided to try it out. It was a little on the sweet side.
Pork BBQ - Fresh off the grill, Ying and I ordered some of their pork bbq. The pork was tender and lathered in bbq, it was amazing.

Total price - 640 PHP ($12.90)

If you‚Äôre looking for a local Filipino restaurant in Manila that I think serves some of the best Filipino food, Aling Sosing's is a restaurant you‚Äôre going to want to check out. The food is awesome, the setting and positive atmosphere is refreshing, and the constant smoke from the grill will keep your nose happy and wanting more!

Aling Sosing‚Äôs Carinderia
Address: Palanan 5819 Zobel Roxas, Palanan Makati City, Philippines
Open hours: 8 am - 6 pm from Monday - Saturday

Video Title: 15-Hour Filipino Food Tour in Pampanga & Manila, Philippines - HUGE LECHON with Makansutra!
Video Description:
Thank you for watching this 15 hour Filipino food tour with World Street Food Congress!
‚ñ∫Subscribe here: http://bit.ly/MarkWiensSubscribe
‚ñ∫Follow my Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/migrationology/

‚ñ∫31 May - 4 June: If you happen to be in Manila from 31 May - 4 June, check out the World Street Food Congress 2017 event (http://wsfcongress.com/). There‚Äôs going to be some seriously delicious food from around the world there! I had another travel commitment during that time, so I won‚Äôt be able to attend, but I know the food will be awesome.

World Street Food Congress: http://wsfcongress.com/
KF Seetoh: https://www.instagram.com/kfseetoh/
Eat and Shout: https://www.instagram.com/eatandshout/
 
The World Street Food Congress and KF Seetoh from Singapore, invited me to attend a 15 hour Filipino food frenzy safari, and was excited to be a part of it! We started in Manila, then went to Pampanga for the main part of the tour, and then returned to Manila to eat more, and end with a grand finale lechon!

1. Bulaluhan sa Espa√±a - We started off this Filipino food tour at about 7 am in Manila at a restaurant called Bulaluhan sa Espa√±a, known for serving bulalo, a beef bone marrow soup. It was pretty tasty, a great way to get started, and my kind of a local restaurant.

2. Atching Lillian - Pampanga is known for being the food culinary capital of the Philippines, and we first went to Atching Lillian, who is legendary for preserving local cuisine. We had some interesting home-cooked Kampangan dishes, and some Filipino tamales.

3. Taldawa - This was probably my favorite stop on this Filipino food tour of Pampanga, a restaurant that specializes in goat and duck. The duck adobo and goat kaldereta were amazing.

4. 25 Seeds - On the food tour we had Chef Sau Del Rosario, a renowned Filipino chef from Pampanga, and just an awesome guy. We next went to his restaurant called 25 Seeds where we were treated to sisig paella, a creation by KF Seetoh and Chef Sau Del Rosario. It was an incredible combination.

5. Susie‚Äôs Cuisine - This place is well known throughout Pampanga for their Filipino desserts. I‚Äôm not big on desserts, but I tried a few bites, and that was about enough for me.

6. Makansutra Hawkers - Since this food tour event was also a press conference for the actual street food event, we then went to Makansutra Hawkers for a quick conference and more Malaysian / Singaporean food, which was excellent.
7. Zubuchon Lechon - I know there are infinite debates about Filipino lechon, or roast pig, but we went to a place that‚Äôs originally from Cebu, but they opened a branch in Manila, known as Zubuchon Lechon. It was pretty awesomely good, so extremely crunchy on the outside and creamy soft on the inside.

World Street Food Congress 2017 ‚Äì If you‚Äôre in Manila from 31 May ‚Äì 4 June 2017, don‚Äôt miss eating at World Street Food Congress 2017. It‚Äôs going to be a huge event, with a curated selection of street food hawkers that I can almost guarantee will impress your taste buds.

Thank you to Makansutra and the Philippine Department of Tourism for inviting me on this Filipino food tour!

Video Title: Philippines Street Food - The ULTIMATE Filipino Food Tour of Quezon City, Metro Manila!
Video Description:
Check out this amazing Filipino street food in Quezon City, Philippines!
‚ñ∫Subscribe to my YouTube channel for more food videos: http://bit.ly/MarkWiensSubscribe
‚ñ∫Follow my Instagram for current updates: https://www.instagram.com/migrationology/

First of all, I want to say a big thank you to my friend Reby for accompanying Ying and I on this Filipino street food tour of Quezon City. She loves to eat, and she‚Äôs just an awesome person!

Quezon City is a city next to Manila, and it‚Äôs actually a bigger city than Manila, but it‚Äôs part of Manila. So for this Filipino street food tour, I met up with my great friend Reby, who is from Quezon City, and we hit the streets to find some incredibly delicious food. Here‚Äôs everywhere we went and the dishes that we ate.

University of the Philippines Diliman - The University of the Philippines is known throughout Manila for its street food stalls, mainly because lots of students gather on campus to enjoy delicious food and hang out.

Rodic‚Äôs Diner - Tapsilog - 95 PHP ($1.91) - We began at Rodic‚Äôs Diner a legendary diner at University of Philippines and tried their legendary tapsilog. This is a well known Filipino food dish that includes cured carabao (water buffalo) meat, topped over rice, with a fried egg on top as well. It makes a great breakfast dish, and it was a great way to start the day off with. Outside of the student center, you‚Äôll find some other Filipino street food carts selling snacks like cheese ice cream (20 PHP ($0.40) and cheese corn (20 PHP ($0.40).

Mang Larry's Isawan (Isaw - 60 PHP ($1.21) total) - Probaby the most famous street food at University of Philippines in Quezon City is Mang Larry's Isawan, a stall that serves grilled skewers of mostly pig and chicken intestines. The intestines and nice and clean, and grilled over hot fire, before you get them. When you get your skewers, you dip them in vinegar, or more like drown them in vinegar, and eat. They were truly incredible, like little bites of hollow crunchy sausage.

Lagro Market - Continuing our Filipino street food tour of Quezon City, Reby brought us to a local market called Lagro Market. As soon as we arrived I noticed one of the coolest rotisserie chicken street food carts that I‚Äôve ever seen, and we had to make a stop and try some of their chicken (lechon manok (roast chicken). The chicken was alright, a little dry, but tasty, and the setting and atmosphere, plus the chicken street food cart, was very cool. Half chicken - 85 PHP ($1.71).

Buko (30 PHP ($0.60) - Buko is the word for young coconut, and there‚Äôs nothing more refreshing than a young coconut on the streets of Manila.

Mango shrimp paste (7 PHP ($0.14) per piece) - Although this is a humble easy Filipino street food snack, it‚Äôs one of my favorites. A sour green mango is cut, then topped with spicy shrimp paste and you eat it like a caramel apple. 

Marawi, Mindanao, Philippines Food - We ended this Filipino food tour by going to a random street food stall that we came across, located across the street from the market. The little stall was serving a type of cuisine from Marawi, located on the Southern Philippines island of Mindanao. It was also Halal food, and they had a variety of typical Filipino food dishes like adobo, but also some Filipino dishes I had never tried before due to the regional differences. Although it looks simple and humble, Reby, Ying and I, all thought the food was fantastic. These are the type of street food stalls that I love to eat at most! Total price - 230 PHP ($4.62)

Thank you again to Reby for showing us around and for the delicious Filipino food tour of Quezon City!

Video Title: Best Filipino Food - Must-Eat GRILLED MILKFISH in Manila, Philippines!
Video Description:
For me, grilled bangus (milkfish) is one of the best Filipino foods!
‚ñ∫Subscribe to my YouTube channel for more food videos: http://bit.ly/MarkWiensSubscribe
‚ñ∫Follow my Instagram for current updates: https://www.instagram.com/migrationology/

Pochok Bangusan is a local carinderia in Quezon City that serves an amazing version of grilled bangus, which is grilled milkfish, and it happens to be one of my personal favorite things to eat in the Philippines. The local restaurant is family fun, and they have all the typical Filipino food dishes set up and pre-cooked at the front of the restaurant when you arrive. All the dishes you can point to and choose from are delicious, but the real magic of eating at Pochok Bangusan is their grilled milkfish. Milkfish is the national fish of the Philippines, and it‚Äôs something that you have to eat when you‚Äôre there.

To make their grilled bangus (milkfish), they first flame grilled the fish, and I mean when he stuck it on the grill, it ignited into flames as the oiliness of the fish touched the hot coals. The fire was also fanned to keep it flaming hot throughout the grilled process. After grilling the fish on both sides, he then flipped it over on the skin side down, and topped it with a few heaping spoons of green tomato relish. The fish was creamy and sort of dry like a tuna, and the green tomato topping was sour and oniony. It was a perfect combination of ingredients.

Along with the grilled milkfish, Ying and I also chose a number of other Filipino food dishes that were already prepared including chicken organs adobo (I would highly recommend it if you like organs like we do), menudo which was a little different than any other version of menudo I‚Äôve had, bulalo which is a famous Filipino food of bone marrow soup, and another of the of my favorite Filipino dishes that I tried for the first time, which was a roasted eggplant topped in krill paste / shrimp paste, and topped with a handful of chopped green mango. 

The combination of all the foods we ordered, and especially the grilled milkfish, is was really made eating at Pochok Bangusan so memorable. Additionally, the family that runs the carinderia (local Filipino food restaurant / street food restaurant) were very friendly and you could tell that they enjoyed the food they were cooking and their customers.

If you‚Äôre looking for wonderful Filipino local food in Manila (it‚Äôs actually in Quezon City, but in Metro Manila), Pochok Bangusan is a fantastic place to eat.

Thanks to https://coconuts.co/manila/food-drink/carinderia-crawl-e22-grilled-bangus-and-bulalo-pochok-bangusan/ for the recommendation.

Pochok Bangusan
Address: 739-C Don Roces Avenue, Quezon City, Philippines
Open hours: 7 am - 10 pm daily
Prices: Our total bill for everything came to 735 PHP

Video Title: Philippines Food in Manila - Best BANANA EGG ROLLS (Turon) at Mang Tootz Food House!
Video Description:
‚ñ∫Subscribe for more food videos: http://bit.ly/MarkWiensSubscribe
‚ñ∫Follow my Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/migrationology/
‚ñ∫Best Filipino street food: https://migrationology.com/filipino-street-food-philippines/
 
Mang Tootz Food House is a famous Philippines food restaurant in Manila, located in the heart of the city next to University of Santo Tomas. Because it‚Äôs next to a major university, it attracts quite a crowd of hungry students everyday, along with anyone else passing by and ready to eat a delicious Filipino food meal and some of the best banana egg rolls (turon) you‚Äôll ever try.
 
Mang Tootz Food House is a carinderia, a local style eatery, and to eat you go up to the front of the restaurant and pick and choose the different dishes you want to try. I got a plate of Bicol express, inihaw na liempo, sisig, chicken kebab, ginataang langka, and finally, their banana rhuma, which is what they call their version of banana egg rolls, or banana lumpia, or turon.
 
Out of the Filipino dishes I ordered, the Bicol express, a Filipino stew of pork with coconut milk and chilies, and the ginataang langka, a jackfruit stew with coconut milk, were my favorite dishes of the meal. The chicken kebab wasn‚Äôt my favorite dish as it was covered in a mayonnaise tasting sauce.
 
Banana-rhuma (turon) - Ok finally, when you eat at Mang Tootz Food House, the one sure thing you have to order is their banana rhuma. These little banana egg rolls are amazing, and you‚Äôll see them at the front of the restaurant being made and deep friend. Many people come by in the afternoon and order only the banana egg rolls, just as a snack to go. They take a lumpia wrapper, place a piece of banana on the inside, wrap it up, and deep fry it in a wok to a crispy golden crunch. The banana egg rolls are then stir fried with a caramel like mixture,and sprinkled with sesame seeds. I‚Äôm not a big sweets lover, but when Filipino turon are hot and fresh, they are truly amazing, and these were the best I‚Äôve ever tried.
 
Total price for meal - 365 PHP ($7.34)

Video Title: Manila Chinatown (Binondo) Food Guide - BLACK CHICKEN SOUP and Chinese Filipino Food in Philippines!
Video Description:
‚ñ∫Subscribe to my YouTube channel for more food videos: http://bit.ly/MarkWiensSubscribe
‚ñ∫Follow my Instagram for current updates: https://www.instagram.com/migrationology/

Binondo, which is Chinatown in Manila, Philippines, is one of the best places to eat when you‚Äôre in Manila. You‚Äôll find a good range of Chinese Filipino food, and overall, I was pleasantly surprised how friendly, clean, and nice it was. Binondo is also known to be the world‚Äôs oldest Chinatowns, and it really has some old style charm to it, and some delicious food to eat.

On this particular Manila Chinatown food tour, my wife Ying and I set off in the morning to just walk around and eat what we saw. I had done some research and wrote down some places to eat, but we were just going to go ourselves and get a feel for walking around and see if we could find any other food. About halfway through the day, we were filming, and we randomly bumped in Nathan who watches our videos. He not only is from Manila, but he‚Äôs also from Manila Chinatown, and he brought us around for the rest of this food tour - so big thank you to Nathan and his fiance!

Here are the place we ate on this Chinese Filipino food tour of Manila Chinatown (Binondo):

Dong Bei Dumplings - This restaurant is legendary in Chinatown Manila for their pork and chive dumplings - 150 PHP ($3.01). The dumplings seemed a little on the expensive side, but they were pretty awesomely delicious. It was a great way to start this Binondo food tour.

Estero Fast Food - Next, we stopped at a restaurant called Estero fast food, serving all sorts of Chinese Filipino street food. We ordered buttered chicken, fried frog legs, stuffed squid, and finally mixed vegetables. The food was all OK, nothing really stand out to me, and wasn‚Äôt a huge fan of the buttered chicken. Total price - 650 PHP ($13.05)

Ho-Land Hopia and Bakery - This is a legendary bakery in Manila‚Äôs Binondo, and they are especially known for their original mung bean pastry hopia. Hopia original - 48 PHP ($0.96)

New Po Heng Lumpia House - After meeting up with Nathan and his fiance, we headed first to go eat some lumpia. The lumpia was excellent, among the best fresh Chinese lumpia I‚Äôve ever had. Lumpia - 60 PHP ($1.20)

Siopao - Nathan knew of this hole in the wall spot, and their siopao were delicious, so fluffy and packed with flavor. Price - 20 PHP ($0.40)

Serry Restaurant - Eating at Serry Restaurant in Binondo was the highlight of this Manila Chinatown food tour for me. We first had Soup Number Five (Soup #5), a notorious bull penis soup, and it was actually incredibly delicious. I loved it. Also, the black chicken soup was incredibly good, very herbal and very clean tasting. Total price - 280 PHP ($5.62)

899 Restaurant - Finally, to end this Chinatown tour, Nathan took us to one of his favorite restaurants in Binondo called 899, especially to eat pig intestines and braised tongue. The tongue was absolutely sensational, while both the big and small intestines were also delicious. Total price - 650 PHP ($13.05)

When you‚Äôre in Manila, walking around Binondo, Manila‚Äôs Chinatown, is one of the best things to do. You‚Äôll find some great food, and it‚Äôs just a fun place to walk around and explore on foot. Thank you to Nathan for his help in this video!

Video Title: FIRST IMPRESSIONS of MANILA Philippines + Food in Manila | Makati, Intramuros + Chinatown!
Video Description:
Our FIRST IMPRESSIONS of MANILA, Philippines as we travel around the city and enjoy a mini Manila Philippines FOOD TOUR! We‚Äôve finally made it to PHILIPPINES‚Äô BIG CITY and we decided to travel around to some of Manila‚Äôs best neighborhoods during our FIRST TIME in Manila and see  the best things to do in Manila! #manila #firstimpressions #philippines  

Starting out on our Manila Philippines Tour in beautiful Makati Manila, we head over to the Manila Sunday Market, Legazpi Market to get a taste of a more local side of Manila‚Äôs financial center and kick off our time in Metro Manila with a Manila food tour.   

Next up we headed to Manila Chinatown to Indulge in Manila Philippines Street Food, where you can find a variety of delicious treats in a Binondo food trip. We also made a stop over to the Luckytown Mall in Chinatown to get out of the heat and humidity during our Manila Philippines city tour.

We wrap up our first day at the iconic Intramuros Manila, a historic walled city within the city, and visit its most famous and oldest stone church in the Philippines. We ended up our night on top of the Bayleaf Hotel to admire the stunning views of the city and sunset overlooking the famous Manila Bay.

We finish up on a second day back in Makati City Philippines for one last halo halo during our time in the Philippines. People originally told us not to spend much time in Manila, but our FIRST IMPRESSIONS OF MANILA left us extremely impressed and we are glad to have explored the city!

Video Title: Finding the BEST restaurants on Siargao Island, Philippines üáµüá≠
Video Description:
Our PHILIPPINES Travel Guide ‚û°Ô∏è https://parttimetravellingfamily.co.uk/product/philippines-travel-guide 
Finding a Filipino restaurant was more difficult than we could possibly imagine. Most of the restaurants on Siargao Island are western. We did find a traditional filipino restaurant in the end and it was definitely worth the wait. Sisig, Inasal, Crispy Pata, Taba ng talangka, Pancit Palabok Bulalo, Lechon, Adobo. 
Our first day on Siargao Island and we have fallen in love. This place is so chilled... so friendly. This is our favourite Island so far. We will be exploring the beautiful Island of Siargao for the next few days so please follow along on our journey. Any recommendations appreciated... Thank you Philippines... the Filipino people have been amazing! üñ§

Video Title: First Impressions of Manila, Philippines üáµüá≠ | Intramuros Walking Tour | Filipino Street Food
Video Description:
Join us as we take a walking tour of one of the oldest neighborhoods in Manila, Philippines. This is the Intramuros - or walled city - district dating back to the 1500s. We began our day with a delicious hearty silog breakfast. Just down the street, all within walking distance, we were able to visit the historical San Angustin Church, the Manila Cathedral, and Fort Santigo. We even walked down into the dungeons of the Fort, which definitely gave us a creepy vibe. After exploring there, we headed back to the Rizal Park area for delicious Filipino street food. Granite enjoyed deep-fried quail eggs (known as kwek-kwek) and Kelly found a palm sugar tofu treat (called Taho).

Video Description:
Head to https://squarespace.com/bagspackedfamily to save 10% off your first purchase of a website or domain using code bagspackedfamily

Manila, Philippines, has a huge variety of food options and street food restaurants. In the time that we have, we will try to explore as many of those neighborhoods as possible. In this video, we spend the day exploring Binondo (Chinatown) in Manila. We find so much delicious Chinese street food and we are able to feed our family just by sampling a variety of different dishes. When we get to a new place, we like to eat a sampling of yummy foods. If we eat one big meal, then we miss out on so many different dishes. That is why you will see us split and share dishes when we are exploring street foods and local small businesses. 

Today, we make 7 different stops for street food! Check out the time stamps listed below for the names of each stop we made. It takes us all day, but we are happy and have full tummies. If you are in Manila, add the Binondo Chinatown neighborhood to your stop. The food is fantastic and we were only able to scratch the service of what there is here.

Video Title: $10 FILIPINO STREET FOOD TOUR at UGBO in TONDO Manila, Philippines üáµüá≠ | MUKBANG Philippines
Video Description:
If you want off-the-beaten-path Filipino street food, with a more local (less touristy) feel, head to UGBO in the Tondo District of Manila. This place was busy with a younger crowd, with lots of music and action going on. The entire street is just one food vendor after another. We really only spent time on this one street, so I‚Äôm sure we missed a lot, as well. We were able to get a taxi here and back to our hotel with no problem. There were many tuk-tuk trucks passing through there, too. We never figured out how to get on one of those, so that is something we will have to try when we come back. In this video, we eat, eat, and eat some more. We had fried foods, meat on a stick, popcorn, empanadas, and the dessert YOU suggested: Halo Halo! Kelly found a twister potato (and off camera she found fresh chili and garlic peanuts). It was a full night of eating. We met so many fun kids running around. 

We love that YOU get to join us around the world. The Bags Packed Family community has grown so much over the last few months and we appreciate all of your support. Stick with us as we explore more of the Philippines, heading to Cebu and Palawan soon.

Video Title: $5 FILIPINO STREET FOOD TOUR at QUIAPO MARKET in Manila, Philippines üáµüá≠ | Mukbang Philippines
Video Description:
If you like street food, join us as we explore the ‚ÄúOld Downtown of Manila‚Äù district, also known as Quiapo. It is famous for the Quiapo Church and the annual festival of the Black Nazarene. Quiapo is also known for its variety of cheap eats and delicious street food. In this video, we go in search of street food. We make many stops ranging from soups, sweets, and fried or grilled meats. Forest finds a delicious dragon fruit juice stand and later makes friends with the sweetest street vendor. It is a full day of eating! The flavors and textures are fantastic contrasts of sticky rice and grilled squid, fried fish balls, and mini ‚Äúmartabak-style‚Äù pancakes. We were actually in search of balut, a poached chicken embryo. Unfortunately, we never found it in Quiapo. Who knows, we probably passed it without even knowing it (or maybe it is served at a specific time of day)? However, we did find it days later, and we can‚Äôt wait to show you that video. 

We love that YOU get to join us around the world. The Bags Packed Family community has grown so much over the last few months and we appreciate all of your support. Stick with us as we explore more street food options in Manila, plus we visit a mall and an amusement park.

Video Title: Exploring ENORMOUS Filipino Church Castle
Video Description:
Our visit with Filipino family in Cebu, Philippines continues with a weekend morning trip to the local Sibonga Market. We look for food to get for brunch and take it home to eat. We get to try fresh mango and an avocado smoothie made with avocado, condensed milk, and crushed ice. We also visit an enormous nearby church called the Monastery of the Holy Eucharist or Simala Church. People come from all over the Philippines to bring offerings for the Virgin Mary in exchange for miracles. We couldn't get over the sheer size of this church. It's been expanded to accommodate the thousands of people who regularly visit. Have you ever seen anything like it?

Watch our next video where our trip to the Philippines continues...

Video Title: Trying My Husband's Favorite Filipino Foods (Bacolod Food Tour)
Video Description:
We are headed on a self-led Filipino food tour in Bacolod, Philippines so I can try Mico's favourite Filipino foods in his hometown! Bacolod City is regarded as one of the best places to eat in all of the Philippines, and they have some incredible iconic dishes and restaurants here. Bacolod City is most well known for being the creator of chicken inasal, which happens to be Mico's favourite food in the world! To get the highest quality chicken inasal, we went to Makbang Country, which translates to chicken country. Chicken inasal sounds simple - it's essentially BBQ chicken, BUT between the special marinade, the iconic chicken oil, and the dipping sauce that only Filipinos know how to make, chicken inasal becomes so much more than just BBQ chicken. Not to mention that the parts of the chicken you eat are...well... not what this Canadian-raised woman is used to. Mico wasn't going to let me get away without trying tinae (intestine) and atay (liver) in addition to the more-familiar paa (leg). 

Something you may not know about Filipino food it that it is meat HEAVY. Like...really heavy! Filipino food is the most meat heavy cuisine we have ever come across, so of course, our second dish of the day was soup made with a massive beef bone. The dish is called cansi, and we went to Sharyn's Cansi House to try it (Sharyn's Cansi House is famous for the dish in Bacolod). The difference between this beef soup and others I've tried is the bone marrow... which Mico so kindly shows me how to eat Filipino-style.,

Batchoy was dish #3, and it was really surprising. It is filled with pancit noodles, which really excited me because pancit is my favourite Filipino food! As soon as I took my first bite of batchoy I was totally surprised. It was not at all what I expected, but I was happy to have a little less meat in my meal üòÇ

Our last dish may not have been classically Filipino, but it is very famous in Bacolod City and came highly recommended by many locals from Bacolod. It was a delicious dessert dish that we got from Calea, and it was the perfect way to cap off our Filipino food tour!

If you want to watch our whole journey through the Philippines so far (including when Nicole's parents came to visit us and spent 3 weeks traveling the country with us), check out this playlist! https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLSSlYnwzYFH4bxzFL6VgocNDTy_P_FfcW

Video Title: First Time Trying Halo Halo In The Philippines üáµüá≠
Video Description:
Today we tried Halo Halo & Kwek Kwek for the first time here in The Philippines! 

We headed to Quiapo market here in Manila in search of our first Filipino Halo Halo. 

Ended up in Jolli dada's eatery just outside the Quiapo market and ordered 2 Halo Halo at 80 PHP each. 

I've gotta say it was alright but I was expecting more it wasn't too sweet and just not as flavourful as the shaved ice desserts we've had in numerous other countries. 

We then bought some ground Filipino coffee across the road, we payed about 150 PHP for some Sagada coffee from Northern Luzon and it's pretty good.

On the way home we stopped at an absolute classic Filipino street food stall for some Kwek Kwek and Siomai. 

The people running this stall in Binondo are super nice and friendly and the food is alright it fills a hole and is super cheap we spent 70 PHP on some Kwek Kwek, Siomai and a coconut juice.
