Video Title: Hungry Vlogger's 48 hour Filipino Street Food Binge üáµüá≠
Video Description:
I started my Filipino street food adventure in the Malate area of Manila, looking for some Pancit.

Before I could find a pancit restaurant I found a street vendor selling ube ice cream. It's not a good idea to eat sweet food before a meal, but I couldn't resist. I love the taste of ube, the purple yam that's used in so many Filipino desserts, and had never tried it in ice cream before.

While buying the ice cream cone, another vendor sold me a pack of boiled quail eggs, and they came in useful later.

I strolled around the Malate area, enjoying my ice cream, then got back to my original mission, the Pancit hunt.

I found a restaurant on Google Maps, Rita's Pancit Malabon. It seems that there are many varieties of Pancit and Pancit Malabon is one of them.

The Pancit Malabon that I was served was a bowl of rice noodles, soaked in a yellow sauce that was tangy, fishy and spicy. Not what I was expecting at all, but tasty nonetheless. And that's where the quail eggs came in, as I added them to my bowl of pancit for extra flavour and protein!

The pancit meal was quite salty, so I went on the hunt for a refreshing drink. I came across a vendor selling a mysterious black liquid they said was Gulaman. I had no idea what it was, and after tasting it I have no idea how to describe it. At only 10 pesos per cup it's a bargain though.

Strolling towards Dolomite Beach with my cup of Gulaman in hand, I found some more street food that I couldn't resist. Turon is a hot, crispy delicious banana spring roll. Deep fried and delicious.

I'd eaten the Turon before at the Filipino Mall in Kuala Lumpur, so I knew what it was and I knew it was tasty. The Manila street food version of Turon was a huge portion size and covered in caramel. What an incredible sweet treat.

I took a walk past the American embassy and Dolomite beach, when I met a magician who was keen to show me his tricks. He entertained me so I bought a couple of his overpriced magic tricks and took them back to my hotel to play with.

After a late afternoon swim in the New Coast Hotel swimming pool, I was back out in Malate for a haircut and trip to Denny's but that wasn't included in the vlog.

The next day my Filipino street food adventure continued and I enjoyed some Tapsilog from a local restaurant.

Tapsilog is a combination of Tapa and Silog. Tapa is something like a beef jerky and Silog is rice and egg. It's a meal that's normally eaten for breakfast but is nice at any time of the day in my opinion.

After that salty meal I was again on the hunt for a cold drink, and again found a vendor selling Gulaman. I'd never heard of it before but it must be a popular drink in the Philippines.

After avoiding some tourist scammers on the streets of Malate, I bargained for a Trike ride to Divisoria market. They were asking me for 500 pesos, but I had a good idea of what the real price was and ended up paying 200 pesos. The price for an air conditioned car on the Grab app was 285 pesos, so they were really trying it on asking me for 500 for the trike ride.

At Divisoria market I bought myself a cool new baseball cap, enjoyed a Graham Fudge Sundae at Jollibee and then enjoyed a nice sunset stroll back to my Malate hotel. Walking is surely faster than being in rush hour traffic anyway!

Video Title: üáµüá≠ Outdoor Filipino Home Invasion. ‚Ç± SURPRISE for Filipino Mother. (Touching)
Video Description:
‚ñ† DALAHICAN, SAN JOSE, ROXAS, ORIENTAL MINDORO, PHILIPPINES: Subscribe and follow me as I invade a Filipino home with the most hard-working people you will ever meet! You won't believe how they live üáµüá≠. 

Nothing beats seeing how people live. NOTHING! Whilst touring the Philippines I often rode past little communities of houses barely standing in close proximity to rivers and the ocean. I just never got around to visiting one. 

When I was touring Mindoro, an island in the Philippines, I once walked past such a community. Sadly, I was on a deserted section of the beach. This wasn't the day for a 'J.C. Invades,' until I turned the corner and came upon these outdoor houses and decided to try to learn more about how they lived. 

After an hour of viewing how pulang buntot fish were rationed throughout the village and climbing my way up a destroyed home, I gained natural courage and started to roll tape. This is what ensued.....


#JayCeeMax  

Just like @HaraldBaldr and @TimKyoutube, my Philippines trip was a sight to see. Now it‚Äôs my turn to present my version.

Video Title: Something Filipino in Ecuador | Hornado/Lechon Volcanoes Banana Ba√±os
Video Description:
Description:
There are many things in Ecuador that may be familiar to Filipinos. Ecuador's Hornado is the Philippines' equivalent to Lechon.  Ecuador like the Philippines is located along the Pacific Ring of Fire where volcanos and earthquakes are common.  Ecuador like the Philippines has taken advantage of the abundant underground heat source for geothermal energy production. Both Ecuador (Amazon rainforest) and the Philippines are recognized by the United Nations as the most biodiversity-rich countries of the world. Ecuador and the Philippines are two of the world‚Äôs top banana producers.  Like the streets of Manila, there are so many streets dogs in Ecuador.

Video Title: ULTIMATE Street Food Tour in Davao City Philippines - EATING WHOLE FILIPINO DURIAN + SATAY & BULALO
Video Description:
Ultimate street food tour in Davao City, Philippines. Davao City has some tasty food and we went on a huge food tour eating a whole Filipino durian, satay and bulalo throughout the city.

üîî SUBSCRIBE FOR MORE FOOD ADVENTURES: https://www.youtube.com/HungryTwoTravel?sub_confirmation=1
üëÄ WATCH I Spent My Birthday at Mcdonalds in the Philippines!: https://youtu.be/EtkPVsWpXbU

We started off our ultimate street food tour in Davao City Philippines trying satti. Filipino satay is covered in a thick, sweet, spicy and savoury sauce that‚Äôs thick like gravy and oh so delicious! A great breakfast that‚Äôs for sure. After our satay, we went to try the popular Filipino food bulalo at a popular shop here in Davao City. Served many times to the former president Duterte, this popular bulalo shop serves a bulalo that‚Äôs so massive you definitely need to share.

Known as the durian capital of the Philippines, the durian here is abundant and affordable. We headed down to the local fruit stands to get a whole Filipino durian to share. Eating a whole Filipino durian is probably one of the highlights of our visit so far, we love the taste and flavour, just so delicious! 

Last stop on our ultimate street food tour in Davao City Philippines was to taste some tuna belly and kinilaw. Davao tuna was a great way to end our  street food tour in Davao!

We hope you enjoy this ultimate street food tour in Davao City Philippines, eating whole Filipino durian and trying the local satti Filipino satay and bulalo. Stay tuned for more street food adventures!

Video Title: The Storm Stole Their Food And Home | Philippines | Orphan's Promise
Video Description:
Ever since Myrna became a single mother, food has been scarce for her and her 6-year-old daughter, Mary Joy. Sometimes they would go for weeks at a time only having yams to eat. Over time, Mary Joy became malnourished.

"I help out on my parents' small farm to bring home a little food for my daughter," Myrna told us. "But with nothing but yams, Mary Joy started getting sick and weak."

"I wanted to help my mom plant vegetables," said the little girl. "But I have to stay home when I'm sick."

One year, two powerful typhoons hit the Philippines and destroyed Mary Joy and Myrna's home. The mother and daughter fled their home and took shelter at Myrna's parents' home.

"I was scared," remembered Mary Joy. "The wind was so strong it shook grandma's house. After the storm, my cousins and I all slept on one bed. My mom slept on the cold floor."

"I had no idea how I would be able to rebuild our home," said Myrna. "All the crops on our family farm had been completely washed away in the storm."

Then, Orphan's Promise came to their community. First, we established a food program for Mary Joy and the other malnourished children in the community.

"The chicken and squash taste good," said the little girl with a smile.

"I'm glad Mary Joy gets to eat food that we cannot afford to serve at home," said her mother. "Since the Orphan's Promise feeding program began, she hasn't been getting sick anymore."

But, we didn't stop there. We gave Myrna everything she needed to start a worm farm. The operation allows Myrna to make and sell organic compost to all the farmers in her community, and business is booming! Last but not least, we made sure the mother and daughter had a safe place to live; Orphan's Promise built the two a brand new home to live in!

"We have much more space to move around," said Myrna. "Our new home is a symbol of hope for us. I am very grateful to God who has given me a second chance to be able to provide for my daughter."

"Thank you very much," exclaimed the little girl.

This story first aired January 2016.

ABOUT US:
OrphansPromise.org is a children's ministry of the CBN. We serve orphans and other vulnerable children around the world,  bringing them from At-risk to Thriving.  Come see lives renewed and restored through the transforming power of God‚Äôs love!
  
We partner with local outreaches around the world to provide fundamental care (fulfilling physical, emotional, educational, and spiritual needs) to help orphans and other vulnerable children discover love and enable them to achieve their highest potential.

Video Title: Cooking Filipino Food for my Slovak Family! Did they like it? | I will teach you how to cook Lugaw!
Video Description:
Hi Guys!

If you wanna try and cook Lugaw as well, here are the ingredients I used.

1 Cup Glutinous Rice / Sticky Rice
3 Thumbs Ginger
4 Cloves Garlic
1 Bulb Onion
6-7 Cups Water/Broth (may add more if necessary)
3 Tbspn Cooking Oil
1 Kilo Chicken Thigh (any part you like)
Salt & Pepper to taste
Roasted Garlic and Chopped Spring Onions for garnish

Optional:
Hard Boiled egg
Crispy Fried Pork and Tofu as side
Sauce : Soysauce, Vinegar and Onion with dash of Ground Black pepper

Steps how to cook Lugaw

1. Saute Onion, Garlic and Ginger.
2. Cook Chicken thigh (or any part of chicken you like) and season it with Salt and pepper, cook for 20 minutes
3. Add water or chicken broth.
4. Add the Glutinous or sticky rice (if Sticky rice is not available, you can use normal rice)
5. Bring to boil and cook the rice for another 20 minutes, checking and stirring occasionally. You may have to add water or broth if needed.
6. Season with Salt and Pepper.
7. Cook until chicken is tender and rice is thick.

For Garnish I add roasted garlic and chopped spring onion on top with boiled egg and dashed of ground Black pepper.

You may eat it with Fried Tofu and Pork belly on side with Soy sauce, Vinegar and Onion as a dipping Sauce like what I did in the video.

This is totally optionally but I highly recommend it :)

I hope you guys will like this Lugaw and tell me if you would try it as well!

Video Title: Battle of the Cheesecakes
Video Description:
Cheesecake time! Go to https://surfshark.deals/ANDONG and enter promo code ANDONG for 83% off and 3 months free.

Join us on our journey for the ultimate cheesecake as we try making cheesecakes from around the world. We got everything from an ancient cheesecake to the newest trend of Ube Cheesecake! Our first step to finding the ultimate cheesecake recipe is to bake and eat through the cheesecake history. What's your favourite cheesecake recipe? Tell us where you're from and why you love it so much! (It will totally help us to narrow down various recipes.)

‚ñ∫ Recipes and Modifications

Goat Milk Ricotta: 
https://honestcooking.com/homemade-goats-milk-ricotta/
We used 120ml of lemon juice and extra vinegar.

Savillum Cheesecake:
https://passtheflamingo.com/2017/08/16/ancient-recipe-savillum-cheesecake-roman-1st-century-bce/
We used 100g of honey and 1 tbsp of poppy seed.

Russicher Zupfkuchen:
https://www.chefkoch.de/rezepte/2636361414129018/Russischer-Zupfkuchen.html

NY Style Cheesecake:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ov4u0ARMWKQ&t=93s&ab_channel=Tasty
Instead of 2 cups of sugar, we suggest using 1 cup of sugar.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ElEqCPMeQQ4&ab_channel=CraftPassion
We don't have cake flour here so we made our own with this tip:
https://www.thespruceeats.com/how-to-make-cake-flour-p2-3057755

Ube Halaya:
https://www.yummly.com/recipe/Ube-Halaya-Recipe-_Purple-Yam-Jam_-2405383?prm-v1#directions

Ube No-bake Cheesecake:
https://www.yummy.ph/recipe/no-bake-ube-cheesecake-recipe
If you make your own Ube Halaya, we suggest that you use less sugar or add no sugar to the cheesecake as the ube halaya is can be very sweet.

Video Title: Filipino Spring Rolls LUMPIA-Recipe
Video Description:

Support us on Patreon https://www.patreon.com/tabieats
======================================================

KIrsten's Embroidery
etsy.com/shop/ThreadingLightlyCO

INGREDIENTS:
300g ground meat (pork/beef mixture)
1 tbsp minced garlic or garlic powder
1 tbsp soy sauce
pinch of salt

Video Title: Baon Kainan is Portland's newest Filipino food cart | Here is Oregon
Video Description:
Portland‚Äôs Filipino food scene just grew one cart bigger. Earlier this month, Baon Kainan, meaning ‚Äúto-go eatery‚Äù in Tagalog, joined Vietnamese food cart Matta, as the latest addition to the lot at Metalwood Salvage on Northeast Prescott Street. But you won‚Äôt find lumpia and pancit on the menu. At least for now. Owners and newlyweds Ethan and Geri Leung, both 31, serve up their own twist to classic Filipino cuisine, while paying homage to their heritage. ‚ÄúIt is an expression of what we grew up with as Filipino Americans,‚Äù Geri explained. And while they always start off with how their moms would make a dish, their tagline states that the food is ‚Äúnot your tita‚Äôs cooking.‚Äù

Video Title: Cooking husband's favorite Filipino food sinigang | Nagharvest ng gulay para mag luto ng Sinigang
Video Description:
We Filipinos love this soup called Sinigang. It's a sour soup that when you cook the vegetables  turns brown. In the Philippines we can use fresh fruits to cook this soup to make it sour. We have tamarind, we have guava, kamias and other sour fruit. But we also have those store bought powder that we can easily use. You can use any kinds of vegetables you want on this soup there is no limit and you can use any protein too. Beef, pork or seafood they are all good for this kind of soup. Here in Bosnia we dont have asian store so when I make Sinigang I used lemon juice. It has more of a tart flavor than sour but its still good. Luckily husband bought some sinigang powder in Zagreb last time and some Filipino friends also gave me. If you dont like your greens will turn brown you can blanch it on the soup that is not  yet sour so that it will retain its green color and then you just add them at the last part just like what I did in the video.

Video Title: Unveiling the Best Grilled Pork Belly Recipe | Try it Filipino Style! #shorts
Video Description:
#shorts

Grilled Pork Belly | Filipino Style

These grilled strips of pork belly, or Inihaw na Liempo, are marinated in a classic Filipino barbecue flavor that is sweet, savory, and slightly tangy. Although typically cooked over a charcoal grill, you can conveniently grill them in the oven, too.

Equipment

Convection oven, grill, or air fryer
Baking Sheet

Ingredients

2 pounds pork belly slices ¬Ω"-thick
‚Öì cup + 1 tablespoon soy sauce, regular or light
¬º cup lemon or calamansi juice
‚Öì cup packed brown sugar sub: any sugar
¬º cup banana or tomato ketchup
6 cloves garlic minced or grated
Black pepper to taste

Dipping Sauce:

¬º cup distilled white or cane vinegar
1 tablespoon minced shallot sub:red onion
Bird's eye chilies to taste; chopped
1 teaspoon sugar
Salt and pepper to taste

Instructions

1. Combine soy sauce, calamansi or lemon juice, brown sugar, ketchup, garlic, and ground pepper (to taste).
2. Marinate pork belly slices and refrigerate for 4 to 8 hours.
3. Preheat oven to 425¬∞ F (218¬∞ C). Line a baking sheet with double layers of aluminum foil to make cleanup easier.
4. Arrange pork belly slices in a single layer and bake them for 20 minutes.
5. Over medium heat, cook leftover marinade for about 10 minutes until slightly thickened to prevent cross-contamination.
6. Remove the meat from the oven and brush it with basting sauce on both sides. Return it to the oven for another 20 minutes. Adjust baking time based on the thickness of the meat. The thinner the slices, the faster they cook.
7. To caramelize the outside, broil on low for about 3 minutes. Be careful not to burn them.
8. To make sawsawan or dipping sauce, combine the vinegar, shallot, chilies, sugar, salt, and pepper to taste.

Video Title: Where to Buy FILIPINO BREAD in the United States (ft. Dollycious Goodies)
Video Description:
Where to Buy FILIPINO BREAD in the United States (ft. Dollycious Goodies) | The Kit Chronicles

SUBSCRIBE for more weekly videos: https://www.youtube.com/c/TheKitChronicles/?sub_confirmation=1

One of the things I dearly missed in the Philippines is being able to easily buy Pinoy bread. Bakeries are scattered around the streets and anyone rarely runs into the conundrum of not knowing where to buy one. Thankfully, for us Filipinos who live here in the United States, and those who love Filipino bread regardless of one's ethnicity, I found just where (and from whom) to buy these local favorites when you're craving one.

In this video, I will be joined by my good friend, Dolly. Dolly is a fellow Filipino US immigrant and the owner of Dollycious Goodies. We will be talking about how she started her business as well as the types of bread available for sale. Deliveries are applicable to most states excluding Hawaii and Alaska.

For more information, including the pricelist and the complete list of delivery availability, you can visit their Facebook Page: https://www.facebook.com/Dollycious-Goodies-101344801729161

If you have anymore queries, don't hesitate to message them on Facebook.

Enjoy the video! (Please turn on the Closed Captions/Subtitles so you can follow through with the discussion in the video as the unwanted background noise may muddle with our voices)

#FilipinoBread #PinoyBread

Directions:

Video Title: Melissa Makes Chicken Afritada | From the Home Kitchen | Bon App√©tit
Video Description:
Join Melissa Miranda as she makes Chicken Afritada. This tomato-based Filipino stew marries hearty vegetables, peas, and olives with tender chicken thighs. To amplify the flavors and keep the chicken skin crispy, Melissa roasts the chicken separately from the veg, reuniting them just before plating.

INGREDIENTS
For the chicken:
1 carrot, finely chopped 
1 celery stalk, finely chopped 
¬Ω large yellow onion, finely chopped 
1 red bell pepper, finely chopped 
5 garlic cloves, roughly chopped 
2 Tbsp. olive oil
4-6 skin-on, bone-in chicken thighs (about 2 lb.)
1 cup chicken stock 
1 14.5-oz. can diced tomatoes 
3  bay leaves 
1 Tbsp. soy sauce 
1 Tbsp. fish sauce 
Johnny‚Äôs seasoning salt

For the roasted vegetables:
4 small carrots, roll cut 
8 oz. heirloom potatoes, quartered
2 medium red bell pepper, seeded, cut into bite size pieces
¬Ω cup olive oil
Johnny‚Äôs seasoning salt

To finish:
¬Ω cup frozen green peas 
¬º cup Castelvetrano olives, pitted 
¬º cup Kalamata olives, pitted

Chicken + Sauce Prep 
- Preheat oven to 425. 
- Heat olive oil in a large deep sided skillet until hot. Sprinkle the chicken with salt and pepper then brown the chicken skin side down for 5-7 minutes until golden. Turn the chicken around and brown on the other side for 2 minutes then remove and set aside on a plate. 
- Add the finely chopped carrot, celery, onion and red bell pepper and saute until soft but not browned around 5 minutes. 
- Once soft, add the garlic and bay and saute for another 2 minutes. 
- Add the tomatoes and stock, fish sauce and soy sauce and stir everything together. Taste to see if you need to add more salt and pepper. Finally, add the chicken back to the skillet and place in the oven. Bake for 45 min. 
- Take out and add olives and green peas and roasted veggies. If you want to reduce the sauce, take out chicken and put back on the stove. 
- Skin should be crispy and delicious. 
Roasting Veggies 
- Place your potatoes and carrots in a large bowl and toss with vegetable and salt and pepper and place on a baking sheet tray and place in the oven to roast. (20 min) - Toss your red bell pepper in vegetable oil and place on another baking sheet try and place in oven to roast (10 min)

Video Title: Filipino Ginisang Munggo | Sauteed Mung Beans and Dried Shrimp with Spinach
Video Description:
Ginisang Munggo or Sauteed Mung Bean is a simple Filipino vegetable dish that is usually eaten during Fridays for some reason. Mung beans are soaked in water until soft and then sauteed with dried shrimp. This is best enjoyed with rice.

The ingredients for Ginisang Munggo are as follows:

1 cup mung beans, soaked in 2 cups water for 3 hrs.
4 cloves crushed garlic
1 medium red onion, sliced
1 medium ripe tomato, cubed
1/2 cup dried shrimp
2 to 3 cups beef broth
1 cup fresh spinach
2 tablespoons fish sauce
1/4 teaspoon ground black pepper
3 tablespoons cooking oil

Video Title: Trying Spiciest Filipino Foodüå∂Ô∏èBicol Express and Sili Ice Cream VOLCANO LEVEL!üî•
Video Description:
Hey guys, welcome back to my channel. Today, I will try some of the Philippines' spiciest food.
  
‚ñ∂Ô∏è Please Subscribe: https://www.youtube.com/@RobbieTravels 

There are many different kinds of food in the Philippines. Sometimes¬† It's sour from the coconut vinegar that ages in barrels in the backyard, and it's sweet from the sugar cane that grows tall in the fields of Negros Occidental. But it's not spicy unless you go to Bicol.

Since I am staying in Legazpi, I decided to try their world-famous spicy Filipino food. So, I went to 1st Colonial Grill at Pacific Mall in Legazpi to try it out. This restaurant is known for its unique dishes, like Sili Ice Cream and Bicol Express.

First, I gave their Bicol Express a try. This food is made with chili peppers, shrimp paste, coconut milk, and pork. It's definitely spicy, but it's also very flavorful.

Then, I ordered their Sili ice cream. This ice cream is made with real chili peppers and comes in four levels of heat: Level 1 is not very spicy, Level 2 is a little spicy, Level 3 is very spicy, and Level 4 is Volcano Level.

So I decided to challenge myself and try the Volcano Level. This is the hottest level, and it's not for people who can't handle the heat.

The heat was unbearable, but the flavor was well worth it. The chili peppers give the ice cream a taste I've never had before.

I can't believe I tried it, but it was an exciting experience. If you're looking for a challenge, try the Volcano Level Sili Ice Cream at 1st Colonial Grill.

Then I headed to the Legazpi City Public Market. This market is great for fresh fruits and vegetables, seafood, and souvenirs.

Lastly, I ended my day at Ayala Malls Legazpi. This mall has a lot of shops and places to eat, and it's a great place to relax and do some shopping.

That's all for today's video. Thanks for watching and let me know which food do you want to try?

Video Title: Sugbo Mercado Cebu City‚ú® Must Try Food Market in the Philippines üáµüá≠
Video Description:
Welcome to my Philippines travel vlog! Today, we're thrilled to take you on a delightful culinary adventure to the vibrant Sugbo Mercado in Cebu. Join us, Mads and I, as we embark on a quest to discover the tantalizing flavors of Lechon, Balut, Sisig, and much more! 

‚ñ∂Ô∏èPlease Subscribe: https://www.youtube.com/@RobbieTravels

Nestled amidst the bustling city of Cebu, Sugbo Mercado stands as a culinary haven, a weekend market brimming with the essence of local flavors and culture. 

Every Saturday and Sunday, from 4 pm to 12 midnight, this vibrant marketplace transforms into a symphony of aromas, sights, and sounds, enticing visitors to immerse themselves in Cebu's rich culinary heritage.

As we ventured into Sugbo Mercado, our senses were immediately captivated by the tantalizing aroma of grilled meats and the lively chatter of vendors and patrons. Our first culinary stop was at a stall specializing in Lechon, the iconic roasted pig dish that has become a symbol of Filipino cuisine. The glistening skin, the succulent meat, and the explosion of flavors were an absolute delight to our taste buds.

Next, we dared to try Balut, a fertilized duck egg that is considered a delicacy in the Philippines. While the initial apprehension was palpable, we took a deep breath and braced ourselves for the unique culinary experience. The combination of the soft, flavorful egg and the slightly developed duckling was a testament to the adventurous spirit of Filipino cuisine.

Our culinary journey continued with Sisig, a sizzling dish made from chopped pork ears, cheeks, and liver, seasoned with onions, chili peppers, and calamansi. The contrast of textures, from the crispy pork ears to the soft liver, and the symphony of flavors were an explosion in our mouths.

Beyond the tantalizing flavors, Sugbo Mercado also offered a glimpse into the rich tapestry of Cebu's culture. We wandered through stalls brimming with handcrafted souvenirs, each piece a testament to the artistry and creativity of the local artisans. The vibrant colors, intricate designs, and unique materials spoke volumes about the cultural heritage that has been passed down through generations.

Our hearts were filled with gratitude for the unforgettable gastronomic experiences and the cultural immersion we had just experienced. 

Sugbo Mercado stands as a testament to the vibrant spirit of Cebu, a place where food and culture intertwine to create an unforgettable experience for every visitor.

So, watch the video till the end and share your thoughts in the comments!

Video Title: EASY Sinigang na Baboy (Pork Sinigang)
Video Description:
Pork Sinigang, also called Sinigang na Baboy, is a traditional Filipino soup dish known for its sour flavor. By tradition, the souring ingredient of this dish comes from a tamarind fruit. Through time, this souring ingredient diversed and instead of using tamarind, guava, calamansi, bilimbi (kamias), unripe green mango, or santol can also be used. Today, a popular powdered sour-soup based ingredient called the "Sinigang Mix" is commonly used.

For more information about this recipes, please visit:
http://www.myfilipinorecipes.com/pork-sinigang

Sinigang Ingredients:

2 lbs pork belly, cut into 2-inch pieces
1 package sinigang soup base mix
1 tomato, quartered
1 onion, quartered
1 taro, quartered
3 long chili peppers (siling haba)
1 medium radish (labanos), sliced
3 string beans, cut into 2-inch length
1 eggplant, cut into 2-inch pieces
10 steams of kangkong leaves
2 tablespoons of fish sauce
Water

Video Title: Award-winning chef and TV host highlights Seattle's Filipino food scene - KING 5 Evening
Video Description:
On the PBS show, No Passport Required, award-winning chef and Restaurateur Marcus Samuelsson explores the diversity of immigrant traditions that are now part of American culture.  Samuelsson says, "food to me has always told a deeper more personal story." And he found plenty of examples of that when taking a deep dive into Seattle's Filipino food scene. 

Filipino Food is influenced by Spanish, Chinese and Malaysian traditions. But it has a flavor all its own. 

During his visit to the Northwest, Samuelsson visited iconic spots like The Oriental Mart at Pike Place Market, which just won a prestigious James Beard award. It was named a "2020 American Classic." 

But he also discovered some emerging spots for Filipino food, like Hood Famous now in the Chinatown International District and Archipelago in South Seattle.  

Washington is home to the fifth-largest Filipino population in the United States.

And just last year, state lawmakers voted to make October Filipino American History Month. Samuelsson says this episode celebrating the Filipino food scene reinforces something he keeps learning with each show.

"I've learned we all come from somewhere and we have a sense of pride. But then we want to explore [...] People are passionate about the United States and also about their roots." 

To see the full episode filmed in Seattle, visit PBS' website.

Evening on KING 5 celebrates the Northwest. Watch it LIVE weekdays at 7:30 on KING 5 or streaming on https://www.king5.com/. Find more stories like this on our website: https://www.king5.com/evening

Video Title: FILIPINO DAD COOKS PORK ADOBO
Video Description:
Philippine Adobo (from Spanish adobar: ‚Äúmarinade,‚Äù ‚Äúsauce‚Äù or ‚Äúseasoning‚Äù) is a popular Filipino dish and cooking process in Filipino cuisine that involves meat, seafood, or vegetables marinated in vinegar, soy sauce, garlic, and black peppercorns, which is browned in oil, and simmered in the marinade. It has occasionally been considered as the unofficial national dish in the Philippines. The cooking method for the Philippine adobo is indigenous to the Philippines. Pre-colonial Filipinos often cooked or prepared their food with vinegar and salt to keep them fresh longer in the tropical climate of the Philippines. Vinegar, in particular, is one of the most important ingredients in Filipino cuisine, with four main traditional types: coconut vinegar, cane vinegar, nipa palm vinegar and kaong palm vinegar, all of which are linked to traditional alcohol fermentation.
 
While the adobo dish and cooking process in Filipino cuisine and the general description of adobo in Spanish cuisine share similar characteristics, they refer to different things with different cultural roots. Unlike the Spanish and Latin American adobo, the main ingredients of Philippine adobo are ingredients native to Southeast Asia, namely soy sauce (originally salt), black peppercorns, and bay leaves. It does not traditionally use chilis, paprika, oregano, or tomatoes. Its only similarity to Spanish and Latin American adobo is the primary use of vinegar and garlic. Philippine adobo has a characteristically salty and sour (and often sweet) taste, in contrast to Spanish and Mexican adobos which are spicier or infused with oregano. 

A rarer version without soy sauce is known as adobong puti ("white adobo" or "blond adobo"), which uses salt instead, to contrast it with adobong itim ("black adobo"), the more prevalent versions with soy sauce. Adobong puti is often regarded as the closest to the original version of the Pre-Hispanic adobo. It is similar to another dish known as pinatisan, where patis (fish sauce) is used instead of vinegar.

Ingredients:
3 lbs ‚Äì Pork Belly (big cubes)
1 whole head ‚Äì Garlic (chopped)
3 ea ‚Äì Bay Leaves
1 tbsp ‚Äì Whole Peppercorns
¬Ω cup ‚Äì Vinegar
¬Ω cup ‚Äì Soy Sauce
2 cups ‚Äì Water
